**United States to Deploy 200 Troops to Nigeria for Military Training Amid Ongoing Security Crisis**  
*Washington – 2026‑02‑12*  
Nigeria faces a persistent insurgency led by Boko Haram, its break‑away faction Islamic State West Africa Province (ISWAP), and other bandit and “kidnap‑for‑ransom” groups. The conflict has killed thousands of civilians, with attacks occurring throughout the northern regions. The United States has expressed concern that the Nigerian government has not fully protected Christian communities from extremist attacks, a claim that Nigeria has publicly rejected. [1] [5]  
The deployment marks the first official acknowledgment by the U.S. of a larger ground presence in Nigeria since the Christmas‑day airstrikes. The U.S. has indicated that the partnership will deepen as part of its broader security cooperation in West Africa, which includes military education, training, and joint counter‑terrorism planning. [6]  
The Nigerian government has denied that it fails to protect any specific religious group. Officials say the military’s counter‑terrorism operations target armed factions that threaten both Christians and Muslims alike. President Bola Tinubu has called the U.S. accusations “unfounded” and emphasized that Nigeria is “overrun by bandits and extremists who prey upon Christians and Muslims with equal enthusiasm.” [6]
The U.S. troops will focus on counter‑terrorism tactics, intelligence‑sharing, and the development of strategic and technical capabilities for Nigerian forces. “The American personnel will not engage in combat or have a direct operational role; Nigerian forces will maintain full command authority,” said Maj. Gen. Samaila Uba, spokesperson for Nigeria’s Defense Headquarters. The training will build on an existing U.S. presence that has been operating in Nigeria since late 2025 to help identify terrorist targets. [1] [4] [6]
The United States announced that approximately 200 soldiers will be deployed to Nigeria in the coming weeks to provide training and technical assistance to the Nigerian Armed Forces. The deployment is part of a broader counter‑terrorism partnership between the two countries and will not involve combat operations or direct engagement with hostile groups.  
The United States began airstrikes against Islamic State‑affiliated militants in northwest Nigeria in December 2025. In the same month, President Donald Trump authorized the strikes, and U.S. Africa Command confirmed that a small team of officers had been stationed in Nigeria to support intelligence operations. The new troop deployment expands this effort by adding approximately 200 additional personnel. [2] [4] [6]
While the U.S. deployment will not involve combat operations, it signals a continued U.S. commitment to supporting Nigerian forces in their fight against extremist groups. The outcome of this training initiative will be closely watched by both sides as the security situation in Nigeria evolves.  
